{"Author": "ADB", "CreationDate": "D:20121119165642Z", "Creator": "Microsoft\ufffd Office Word 2007", "Keywords": "adb rrp report recommendation president", "ModDate": "D:20121226161956+08'00'", "Producer": "Microsoft\ufffd Office Word 2007", "Title": "Report and Recommendation of the President", "content": " Project Preparation and Start-Up Support Facility (RRP VIE 45098) \n\nDEVELOPMENT COORDINATION \n \n\nMajor Development Partners: Strategic Foci and Key Activities \n\nA. \n \n1. \nOfficial development assistance (ODA) commitments to Viet Nam have rapidly increased \nto support its social and economic development needs. During 2005\u20132010, $31 billion of ODA \nwas approved for Viet Nam, and this figure is expected to rise to $32 million\u2013$34 billion during \n2011\u20132015. \n \nIncreasing  ODA  commitments  reflect  development  partners\u2019  confidence  in  Viet  Nam\u2019s \n2. \ngrowth performance and ODA projects\u2019 consistent achievement of development results. Despite \nthis, a recent review of the portfolio performance of the 6 Bank  Group, which provides 80% of \nODA  to  Viet  Nam,  indicated  that  slow  implementation  is  a  persistent  problem  affecting  ODA \nprojects, with disbursement performance lagging far behind that of comparable countries in the \nregion1. \n \nIssues underlying slow  project implementation and disbursement  are (i) start-up delays \n3. \nas activities often commence only after loan effectiveness; (ii)  differences in the procedures of \ndevelopment  partners  and  the  government  regarding  project  preparation,  implementation, \nprocurement,  and  safeguards;  (iii)  a  cumbersome  and  lengthy  approval  process;  (iv)  weak \nproject  management  capacity;  and  (v)  failure  to  ensure  the  timely  provision  of  counterpart \nfunding, which affects the quality of project documents and progress in implementation.  \n \nB. \n \n4. \nThese portfolio performance issues have been being discussed and addressed through \nthe  6  Banks  Initiative  and  the  Aid  Effectiveness  Forum  (footnote  1).  The  6  Banks  Group \naddresses  common  portfolio  performance  issues  through  joint  reviews,  analytical  studies,  and \nto  harmonize  procedures  and  strengthen  country  systems.  The  Aid \npolicy  dialogue \nEffectiveness Forum facilitates dialogue between the government and development partners.  \n \n5. \nAchievements  recorded  to  date  are  (i)  common  guidelines  for  feasibility  studies  to \nfacilitate  and  accelerate  project  preparation  and  (ii)  the  aligned  reporting  tool  for  use  in  both \ninternal government reports and reports to development partners, which is intended to ease the \nreporting burden on project management units.  \n \nOngoing  activities  include  (i)  harmonizing  the  development  partners\u2019  project  concept \n6. \npaper  and the government\u2019s  detailed  project  outline  and  (ii)  strengthening country  systems for \nprocurement, social impact assessment, and environment impact assessment. Advance actions \nhave  been  proposed  to  shorten  start-up  delays.  Proposals  have  been  made  to  reform  the \nimprove  government \nproject  management  unit,  simplify  disbursement  procedures,  and \nprocedures  for  counterpart  planning  and  provision  and  for  adjusting  ongoing  projects.  These \nproposals are being discussed with the government in the context of the ongoing revision of the \nlegal framework governing ODA project management. \n \n\nInstitutional Arrangements and Processes for Development Coordination \n\n \n\n                                                \n1 Joint Portfolio Performance Review VII conducted in November 2011  with the 6 Banks:  Asian Development Bank, \nAgence  Fran\u00e7aise  de  D\u00e9veloppement,  Japan  International  Cooperation  Agency,  Export\u2013Import  Bank  of  the \nRepublic of Korea, KfW Development Bank, and World Bank \n\n\fRecommendations \n\n \nC. \n \n7. \nAddressing portfolio performance issues is a long-term process, as reforms often require \nchanges in the legal framework that affect all public investment projects, not just ODA projects. \nEven  under  the  status  quo,  project  implementation  will  accelerate  significantly  if  start-up \nperformance is improved by implementing advance actions and improving the quality of project \ndocuments. Under the current legal framework, financial resources are provided only after loan \neffectiveness, leaving a financial gap that Asian Development Bank assistance needs to fill. \n \n\n\f", "author_pages": ["Recommendations \n", " \nC. \n \n7. \nAddressing portfolio performance issues is a long-term process, as reforms often require \nchanges in the legal framework that affect all public investment projects, not just ODA projects. \nEven  under  the  status  quo,  project  implementation  will  accelerate  significantly  if  start-up \nperformance is improved by implementing advance actions and improving the quality of project \ndocuments. Under the current legal framework, financial resources are provided only after loan \neffectiveness, leaving a financial gap that Asian Development Bank assistance needs to fill. \n \n"], "classified_text": [["Project", "O"], ["Preparation", "O"], ["and", "O"], ["Start-Up", "O"], ["Support", "O"], ["Facility", "O"], ["(", "O"], ["RRP", "O"], ["VIE", "O"], ["45098", "O"], [")", "O"], ["DEVELOPMENT", "O"], ["COORDINATION", "O"], ["Major", "O"], ["Development", "O"], ["Partners", "O"], [":", "O"], ["Strategic", "ORGANIZATION"], ["Foci", "ORGANIZATION"], ["and", "O"], ["Key", "O"], ["Activities", "O"], ["A", "O"], [".", "O"], ["1", "O"], [".", "O"], ["Official", "O"], ["development", "O"], ["assistance", "O"], ["(", "O"], ["ODA", "O"], [")", "O"], ["commitments", "O"], ["to", "O"], ["Viet", "PERSON"], ["Nam", "PERSON"], ["have", "O"], ["rapidly", "O"], ["increased", "O"], ["to", "O"], ["support", "O"], ["its", "O"], ["social", "O"],